        depth: 2,
        title: "Two Worlds, and the World Between Them",
        body: `<p>From the ashes of the Second World War two states emerged larger than the rest: the United States, untouched on its home soil and holding the atomic bomb, and the Soviet Union, bled white by twenty-seven million dead but in command of half of Europe. Each believed it embodied the future of humankind. The American future was capitalism, markets, and liberal democracy; the Soviet future was socialism, planning, and the dictatorship of the proletariat. Between 1945 and 1991 these two visions waged a global contest — the <em>Cold War</em> — that armed itself to the teeth, divided the planet, and yet, astonishingly, never became a direct war between the two giants. They fought everywhere except each other.</p><p>The American journalist Walter Lippmann popularized the name in 1947. It was cold because the central confrontation stayed frozen: no Soviet and American armies ever clashed head-on, deterred by the knowledge that a hot war might end the species. But it was hot wherever it touched the ground elsewhere — in Korea, Vietnam, Angola, Afghanistan, Central America.</p><p>And here the second great story enters. As the superpowers squared off, the old European empires — British, French, Belgian, Dutch, Portuguese — were collapsing. Within a single generation, colonial subjects from India to Ghana to Indonesia became citizens of independent states. These new nations, much of them poor and newly sovereign, became the terrain on which Washington and Moscow competed for allegiance, resources, and proof of their model. To treat the Cold War and decolonization as two separate histories is to miss the point. They were one weather system, each storm feeding the other.</p>`,
        pullQuote: "They fought everywhere except each other."
