        depth: 4,
        title: "The Logic Beneath the Map",
        body: `<p>Beneath the headlines ran a handful of structural ideas that historians and theorists use to make sense of the era. The first is <strong>bipolarity</strong>: a world organized around exactly two centers of power. Unlike the multipolar Europe of the nineteenth century, where five or six great powers balanced one another, the postwar order had two poles, and almost every conflict could be plotted as a tug between them. With bipolarity came the <strong>security dilemma</strong> — the tragic mechanism by which each side's defensive moves look offensive to the other, so that arming for safety provokes the very threat it was meant to guard against. A bomber built to deter becomes, in the adversary's eyes, a bomber built to attack.</p><p>The second idea is <strong>nuclear deterrence</strong> and its mature doctrine, <strong>mutually assured destruction</strong> — the grimly apt acronym MAD. If each side keeps enough weapons safe from a first strike to annihilate the other in retaliation, then rational leaders will never launch. Peace rests, paradoxically, on the credible promise of mass death.</p><p>The third is the <strong>"three worlds" framing</strong> — the First World of the capitalist West, the Second of the communist bloc, the <em>Third World</em> of everyone else. The phrase, coined by the French demographer Alfred Sauvy in 1952 in deliberate echo of the Third Estate of the French Revolution, was meant to dignify the unaligned poor as history's neglected majority. But it flattened enormous differences — lumping India with Bolivia, Egypt with Indonesia — and it implied a ranking it claimed to resist.</p><p>The decisive insight is that decolonization and superpower rivalry <em>fed each other</em>. A new nation choosing socialism, or merely nationalizing a foreign-owned oil company, could look to Washington like a domino falling toward Moscow — and vice versa. So the giants intervened. In Iran in 1953 the CIA and British intelligence helped topple the elected nationalist Mohammad Mossadegh after he nationalized Anglo-Iranian Oil. In the Congo in 1960–61, both superpowers maneuvered around Lumumba, who was murdered with Belgian and American complicity. The struggle for the global South was not a sideshow to the Cold War. For most of humanity, it <em>was</em> the Cold War.</p>`
