        depth: 5,
        title: "The Historian's Evidence",
        body: `<p>For four decades the Cold War was studied largely from one side of the curtain. Western historians had memoirs, congressional records, leaked cables, and the steady drip of American declassification; of Soviet decision-making they had little but inference. Then, between 1989 and 1991, the archives opened. The collapse of the Eastern bloc threw open Soviet, East German, Polish, Hungarian, and eventually partial Chinese records, and the field was transformed almost overnight. The Cold War International History Project, founded at the Woodrow Wilson Center in 1991, began publishing translated documents that let scholars read, for the first time, what Moscow and its allies had actually said to one another behind closed doors.</p><p>Some revelations were spectacular. East German records included the files of the <strong>Stasi</strong>, the state security service, whose surveillance of its own citizens was so total that the archive runs to roughly 111 kilometers of paper plus millions of index cards — a uniquely intimate record of how a police state actually functioned, now open to anyone who files a request. From the American side came <strong>Venona</strong>, a project the U.S. Army Signal Intelligence Service began in 1943 to break partially reused Soviet one-time-pad cipher traffic. Declassified in 1995, the Venona decrypts confirmed the broad outlines of Soviet espionage in the United States — including material implicating Julius Rosenberg — while leaving many cover names unidentified, a reminder that even hard cryptographic evidence arrives full of gaps.</p><p>Two methodological problems sit at the heart of the field. The first is the <strong>counterfactual</strong> built into nuclear history: deterrence is the study of wars that did not happen. We cannot run the experiment. To claim that the bomb "kept the peace" is to assert what would have occurred in a world we never inhabited — a logically slippery move that historians like John Lewis Gaddis and his critics have argued over for decades.</p><p>The second is the problem of <strong>reconstructing covert action</strong>. Coups, assassinations, and secret subsidies are designed to leave no trace. Historians work from layered releases — the U.S. State Department's <em>Foreign Relations of the United States</em> series, documents pried loose under the Freedom of Information Act, the 1975 Church Committee hearings, and the National Security Archive's lawsuits — assembling a mosaic in which the most important tile is often still classified or destroyed. A redaction is itself a piece of evidence; so is a missing file. The discipline has had to become expert at reading silence.</p>`
